Title:
This was my 2nd experience flying Fastjet return between Jhb and Harare. Flying between these 2 cities has to be one of the most profitable routes in sub-Saharan Africa, perhaps 2nd only to the price gouging of other airlines on the Jhb-Gaborone route

Don't fall for the advertising classifying them as a low-cost carrier - On this route, ticket prices range from borderline expensive to deep into rip-off category. Specifically, if you consider that everything from baggage to insurance to onboard drinks and snacks could be charged on top of the basic ticket price. To put their pricing in perspective - for the price 2 adults fly 1120 km to Harare return, 1.5 adults can fly return to Bangkok or Europe (3 or more meals, drinks, snacks and luggage and other niceties included with a distance exceeding 10 x or more further)

- On check-in, the agent tried to force me to pay extra for excess luggage, and after redirecting me to another counter where staff merely assisted queue jumpers first, it turned out luggage was included in the ticket price paid after all;
- On return, we booked a wheelchair for an elderly passenger, which never arrived. No explanation was given, and no effort was made to find somebody to help, despite other airlines' elderly passengers being assisted while we waited ;
- The plane was delayed by +- 1.5 hrs, no adequate explanation given;
- On arrival at Jhb (ORTIA) no wheelchair assistance was available to disembark or inside the airport - staff presumably went home or were sleeping

Fastjet operates both Airbus and Embraer ERJ-190's. On this trip we flew on the Embraer, which is rather noize inside.
